<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="354" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1221]" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1159,1184]" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[914,981,1161,1184]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">trans-</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[1052,1125,1161,1184]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">ovatus</emphasis>
, referring to the gnathos transversely ovate at base in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
